// BAHAI
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#2b6cb0;">⊕ The Baháʼí Faith — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Strictly monotheistic — one unknowable God | <strong>Founded:</strong> 1844 CE, Persia | <strong>Scripture:</strong> Writings of Baháʼu\'lláh, the Báb, and ʻAbdu\'l-Bahá</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Baháʼí faith (iman in Arabic) is rooted in the principle of independent investigation of truth — each person must seek truth for themselves rather than accepting inherited tradition blindly. This makes Baháʼí faith explicitly anti-dogmatic in spirit: one is encouraged to read the sacred writings, apply reason, and arrive at one\'s own sincere conviction. At the same time, once the seeker is convinced of Baháʼu\'lláh\'s claim, full commitment to his teachings and the institutions of the Faith is expected.</p>';
echo '<p>The Baháʼí concept of progressive revelation is central: God has sent a series of divine educators (Manifestations of God) to guide humanity at different stages of its development. Abraham, Moses, Zoroaster, Krishna, Buddha, Jesus, Muhammad, the Báb, and Baháʼu\'lláh are all authentic Manifestations. Each brought teachings appropriate to their era; Baháʼu\'lláh\'s revelation is the most recent and the most appropriate for the current age of global unification.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>The Oneness of God</strong> — absolute monotheism; God is unknowable in essence; all that humans can know of God comes through the Manifestations</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Oneness of Religion</strong> — all major religions are successive chapters of one divine revelation; their differences are products of time, cultural context, and human distortion</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Oneness of Humanity</strong> — the most distinctive Baháʼí social teaching; racism, nationalism, and religious prejudice are spiritual diseases; the establishment of a world commonwealth is a divine goal</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Equality of Men and Women</strong> — full gender equality is a binding Baháʼí principle; both sexes must have equal access to education, opportunity, and legal rights; a woman\'s perspective must be fully represented in governance</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Harmony of Science and Religion</strong> — if religion contradicts science, one of the two is wrong; a religion that contradicts verified scientific knowledge has lost its authority; science without religion becomes materialism; religion without science becomes superstition</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Covenant</strong> — Baháʼu\'lláh appointed ʻAbdu\'l-Bahá as his successor and interpreter; ʻAbdu\'l-Bahá appointed Shoghi Effendi as Guardian; the Universal House of Justice (elected every five years from all Baháʼís worldwide) is the supreme governing institution of the Faith today</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Dogma</h3>';
echo '<p>The Baháʼí Faith has core non-negotiable positions despite its anti-dogmatic spirit:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>The authenticity of Baháʼu\'lláh\'s claim as the Manifestation of God for this age</li>';
echo '<li>The authority of the authorized Baháʼí institutions (the Universal House of Justice)</li>';
echo '<li>The rejection of clergy — the Baháʼí Faith has no priesthood; worship is lay-led</li>';
echo '<li>Obedience to government except where it directly contradicts Baháʼí principles</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>The Baháʼí Faith actively seeks to expand — called "teaching the Faith" rather than proselytism. Baháʼís are encouraged to share their beliefs with others, invite people to devotional gatherings, and establish study circles and children\'s classes open to all. However, the approach is non-confrontational and non-pressuring: the Faith is offered, never imposed. High-pressure conversion tactics are not approved. The Universal House of Justice has consistently emphasized quality of teaching over quantity of conversions.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>A Baháʼí who formally leaves the Faith (covenant-breaking) faces administrative consequences: withdrawal of administrative rights (voting in Baháʼí elections, contributing to the Fund, attending the Nineteen Day Feast). The most severe sanction — "covenant-breaking" (nakz-i-mithaq) — is reserved for those who actively undermine the Faith or its institutions; covenant-breakers are shunned by the community. This is not a violent or legal sanction but a complete social separation designed to protect the community\'s unity. Today apostasy from the Baháʼí Faith is socially difficult in some Baháʼí communities but carries no legal consequence in most countries. In Iran, however, Baháʼí identity itself is persecuted — Baháʼís are executed, imprisoned, and have their property confiscated by the Islamic Republic.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>No formal initiation rite for infants — the Baháʼí Faith has no baptism equivalent</li>';
echo '<li>Children are welcomed into the community; prayers are said for them</li>';
echo '<li>Children\'s classes are a central Baháʼí community institution — spiritual education from an early age</li>';
echo '<li>At age 15, a young person formally declares their own Baháʼí membership — childhood enrollment in the Faith is not binding</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>Marriage requires the consent of both parties AND the consent of all living biological parents (regardless of whether the parents are Baháʼí) — a distinctive and practically challenging requirement</li>';
echo '<li>The wedding ceremony is simple: the couple recite "We will all, verily, abide by the Will of God" before two witnesses; the rest of the ceremony is flexible</li>';
echo '<li>Marriage is encouraged; celibacy is not valued as a spiritual path</li>';
echo '<li>Monogamy is the Baháʼí standard; polygamy is prohibited</li>';
echo '<li>Divorce is permitted but strongly discouraged; a year of "patience" (separation without legal divorce) is required before divorce can proceed</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Death and the Afterlife</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>The soul is immortal; it continues to progress through "worlds of God" after physical death</li>';
echo '<li>Heaven and hell are not physical places but states of nearness to or distance from God</li>';
echo '<li>The dead can be aided by the prayers of the living</li>';
echo '<li>Burial is required — cremation is prohibited (the body should be treated with respect and returned to earth)</li>';
echo '<li>The body must not be transported more than one hour\'s journey from the place of death for burial — a requirement causing difficulty for diaspora communities</li>';
echo '<li>A specific prayer for the dead (Salát-i-Mayyit) is recited at the funeral</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Reincarnation</h3>';
echo '<p>The Baháʼí Faith explicitly rejects reincarnation. The soul progresses through successive "worlds of God" after death — each world more refined than the last — but never returns to the physical world. ʻAbdu\'l-Bahá addressed this directly: the soul\'s journey is forward, not cyclical; physical reincarnation would represent regression, not progress. This is a clear, unambiguous doctrinal position distinguishing Baháʼí teaching from the reincarnation traditions of India and Africa.</p>';

// MORMONISM
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#1a365d;">⊕ Mormonism (LDS) — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Henotheistic/polytheistic in metaphysics; monotheistic in devotion | <strong>Founded:</strong> 1830 CE, USA | <strong>Scripture:</strong> Bible, Book of Mormon, Doctrine and Covenants, Pearl of Great Price</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>LDS faith is built on personal testimony — the individual spiritual witness (typically described as a "burning in the bosom") that the Book of Mormon is true and that Joseph Smith was a prophet. This testimony is considered a gift of the Holy Ghost and the foundation of LDS commitment. The bearing of testimony ("I know that the Church is true...") is a central practice in LDS worship — members regularly share their testimonies publicly in fast and testimony meetings.</p>';

echo '<h3>Distinctive Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>The Godhead</strong> — God the Father (Heavenly Father), Jesus Christ, and the Holy Ghost are three distinct beings, not a Trinity; God the Father and Jesus Christ have perfected, glorified physical bodies; the Holy Ghost is a spirit personage only</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Eternal Progression</strong> — humans are literally the spiritual children of Heavenly Father and a Heavenly Mother; they lived as spirits before birth (pre-mortal existence); on earth they gain physical bodies and moral experience; the highest celestial kingdom offers the possibility of becoming like God ("As man now is, God once was; as God now is, man may become" — Lorenzo Snow)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Plan of Salvation</strong> — pre-mortal life → mortality (a test) → death → spirit world → resurrection and judgment → one of three kingdoms of glory (Celestial, Terrestrial, Telestial) or outer darkness</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Eternal Families</strong> — families sealed in the temple can be together forever; the sealing ordinance (performed only in temples by authorized priesthood holders) is the most emotionally significant LDS doctrine</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Priesthood</strong> — the authority to act in God\'s name; held by worthy male members of the Church; two orders: the Aaronic Priesthood (preparatory, held from age 12) and the Melchizedek Priesthood (higher, conferred on adult men)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Additional Scripture</strong> — the Book of Mormon (ancient American scripture translated by Joseph Smith); the Doctrine and Covenants (modern revelations); the Pearl of Great Price (including the Book of Abraham, claimed to be translated from an Egyptian papyrus)</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Mormonism is among the most actively proselytizing religions in the world. Male members typically serve a two-year full-time mission (ages 18–26); female members may serve an 18-month mission (ages 19+). Approximately 70,000 LDS missionaries serve at any given time in over 180 countries. The white-shirted, name-tagged pairs of missionaries are among the most recognizable symbols of organized religion in the modern world. The Church spends enormous resources on missionary work, including the Mormon Tabernacle Choir, visitors\' centers at Temple Square in Salt Lake City, and sophisticated online outreach.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Formal apostasy from the LDS Church — defined as teaching false doctrine, openly opposing Church leadership, or behavior contrary to Church standards — can result in a membership council (formerly a "disciplinary council") leading to formal disfellowshipment (retaining membership but losing privileges) or excommunication (complete removal from membership rolls). High-profile excommunications of intellectuals, feminists, and LGBTQ+ advocates have generated significant controversy and media attention. Those who simply stop attending ("going inactive") are not disciplined. Individuals who wish to have their names formally removed from Church membership records must submit a written request.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth Traditions</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Baby blessing</strong> — a male priesthood holder (typically the father) gives the infant a name and a formal blessing in the Sunday meeting; this is not baptism and does not confer Church membership</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Baptism at age 8</strong> — LDS doctrine holds that children are not accountable for sin until age 8; baptism is performed at or after this "age of accountability"; baptism by immersion is performed by an Aaronic Priesthood holder</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Confirmation</strong> — immediately after baptism, the newly baptized member receives the gift of the Holy Ghost by the laying on of hands by a Melchizedek Priesthood holder</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage — Celestial Marriage</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>Temple marriage ("celestial marriage") is the highest form of LDS marriage; performed in the temple by an authorized sealer; it seals the couple for time and eternity; only members with current temple recommends may attend</li>';
echo '<li>Non-members and members without temple recommends cannot attend a temple wedding — a source of significant family tension in mixed-faith situations</li>';
echo '<li>In most countries, a civil ceremony must also be performed to meet legal requirements; in the USA and some other countries, the temple ceremony itself is legally recognized</li>';
echo '<li>Polygamy — practiced by Joseph Smith and early Church leaders; officially abandoned in 1890 (the Manifesto) as a condition of Utah statehood; still practiced by fundamentalist splinter groups not affiliated with the main LDS Church</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Death and Burial</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>The spirit leaves the body at death and enters the spirit world — a temporary state where missionary work continues; righteous spirits in paradise; those who did not accept the gospel in mortality may do so in the spirit world</li>';
echo '<li>Temple work for the dead — baptism for the dead (proxy baptism performed in temples by living members for deceased ancestors) is one of the most distinctive LDS practices; it offers everyone who has ever lived the opportunity to accept the gospel in the spirit world; the Church maintains the world\'s most extensive genealogical database (FamilySearch) for this purpose</li>';
echo '<li>Burial preferred over cremation (resurrection of the body), though cremation is permitted</li>';
echo '<li>The deceased is dressed in white temple clothing for burial; endowed members are buried in their temple garments</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Reincarnation</h3>';
echo '<p>Mormonism explicitly rejects reincarnation. Each spirit lives one mortal life; after death, the spirit enters the spirit world and eventually participates in the resurrection (the permanent reunification of spirit and body). The LDS doctrine of pre-mortal existence (spirits lived with Heavenly Father before birth) might superficially resemble reincarnation but is fundamentally different — there is no previous mortal life, and the spirit does not return after death to another mortal body.</p>';

// RASTAFARI
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#276749;">⊕ Rastafari — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Monotheistic — Jah (God) identified with Haile Selassie I | <strong>Founded:</strong> 1930s, Jamaica</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Rastafari defies easy categorization as a "religion" — it describes itself variously as a faith, a movement, a way of life, and a philosophy. There is no central authority, no fixed creed, and no standardized practice beyond certain widely shared convictions. What holds Rastafari together is not institutional structure but shared symbols (the colors, dreadlocks, ganja), shared narrative (Babylon vs Zion, Africa as promised land), shared music (reggae, nyahbinghi drumming), and shared identification of Haile Selassie I as the returned Messiah and fulfillment of biblical prophecy.</p>';
echo '<p>Rastafari is rooted in the prophecy attributed to Marcus Garvey — "Look to Africa for the crowning of a Black King" — and its fulfillment in the coronation of Ras Tafari Makonnen as Emperor Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia in 1930. For early Rastafarians, this event was the fulfillment of Revelation 5:5: "the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David, has triumphed." Haile Selassie himself was a devout Ethiopian Orthodox Christian who never accepted the divine status Rastafarians attributed to him — a theological awkwardness that Rastafarians handle in various ways.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Jah</strong> — the Rastafari name for God (from "Jehovah/Yahweh"); Haile Selassie I is the earthly embodiment of Jah; the divine lives within every person — "I and I" replaces "me" to express the divine-human unity</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Babylon</strong> — the corrupt, oppressive system of white-dominated Western civilization; its institutions (government, police, church, financial system) are instruments of oppression to be resisted</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Zion / Africa</strong> — the promised land; Ethiopia specifically as the spiritual homeland of all Black people; repatriation to Africa (physically or spiritually) is the goal</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Livity</strong> — righteous living; eating natural (ital) food; living in harmony with nature; avoiding the corrupting influences of Babylon</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Bible</strong> — read through an Afrocentric lens; the "true" Israelites are Black Africans whose history has been whitewashed by European translators; King James removed certain books; Ethiopia\'s ancient Jewish/Christian heritage (the Ark of the Covenant in Axum) validates the African claim to biblical identity</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Rastafari spreads primarily through music — reggae, particularly the work of Bob Marley, has introduced Rastafari ideas to audiences in every country on earth. This is not formal proselytism but cultural diffusion of extraordinary power. Marley\'s music has been credited with inspiring social movements, comforting the oppressed, and introducing millions to Rastafari concepts of resistance, dignity, and divine love. No one is sent on missions to convert; one is drawn to the Rastafari way through its music, its philosophy, and the quality of life it advocates.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Rastafari has no formal structure to enforce apostasy rules — there is no membership list to remove someone from. One simply stops living the Rastafari way. The social consequences depend entirely on how embedded one is in a Rastafari community. For committed Rastafarians, leaving the way of life involves leaving a community, a set of practices, and an identity that may be very deeply held. There is no equivalent of Islamic riddah or Catholic excommunication.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth, Marriage, and Death</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Birth</strong>: no formal initiation rite; children are raised in the Rastafari way through family practice and community</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Marriage</strong>: varies by mansion (branch); some Rastafarians practice traditional marriage; the Bobo Ashanti have formal wedding ceremonies; many Rastafarians in the wider movement practice common-law union; patriarchal family structure is traditional in most mansions</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Death</strong>: earlier Rastafari tradition held that the righteous would not die ("Jah people don\'t die — they multiply"); this was connected to a millennarian belief in physical translation to Africa; in practice, Rastafarians die like everyone else; death is understood as transition; elaborate mourning is discouraged; the emphasis is on life and vitality</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Reincarnation</h3>';
echo '<p>Rastafari has no systematic doctrine of reincarnation. The early movement\'s belief in physical immortality for the righteous has given way, in most manifestations, to a more ambiguous understanding of death and transition. Some Rastafarians, influenced by their African heritage, accept ancestral continuation; others, influenced by the biblical framework, emphasize resurrection rather than reincarnation. There is no authoritative Rastafari position on the question.</p>';

// WICCA
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#2d6a1f;">⊕ Wicca — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Duotheistic (Goddess and God) or polytheistic; some practitioners pantheistic | <strong>Founded:</strong> 1954 CE, UK | <strong>Scripture:</strong> No fixed canon; Book of Shadows (personal ritual journal)</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Wicca\'s approach to faith is explicitly experiential and anti-dogmatic. There is no Wiccan creed or binding theology — the tradition actively encourages personal exploration and diversity of belief within certain broad parameters. What makes someone Wiccan is practice, not doctrine: working within the ritual framework (the circle, the elements, the Wheel of the Year), honoring the Goddess and God in whatever forms feel authentic, and living by the Wiccan Rede.</p>';
echo '<p>The divine in Wicca is understood as immanent — present in nature, in the body, in the seasonal cycles — rather than transcendent. The Goddess is the moon, the earth, the sea, and the wild; the God is the sun, the forest, the harvest, and the cycle of death and rebirth. Together they constitute a complete divine polarity — neither is complete without the other.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>The Wiccan Rede</strong> — "An it harm none, do what ye will." The primary ethical statement; total personal freedom is the guiding principle, limited only by the harm caused to others; the harm principle is broadly understood to include harm to oneself, to the environment, and to future generations</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Threefold Law</strong> — whatever energy you put out returns to you threefold; a karmic principle governing magical practice; functions as both ethical incentive (good actions return good) and warning (harmful actions return harm magnified)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Wheel of the Year</strong> — eight seasonal sabbats marking the solar year; the mythological cycle of the Goddess and God through birth, growth, death, and rebirth; the most widely observed Wiccan liturgical structure</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Magic</strong> — the use of focused will and ritual to effect change in accordance with one\'s deepest will; understood as a natural force, not supernatural; "Magic is the art of changing consciousness at will" (Dion Fortune)</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Sacred immanence</strong> — the divine is present in nature; the natural world is sacred; ecological ethics are a spiritual obligation</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Wicca does not proselytize. The traditional principle is "we do not seek converts; those who are meant to find us will find us." Wiccan knowledge was historically transmitted through coven initiation — invitation only, after a year-and-a-day of study. Gerald Gardner\'s public books (1954, 1959) and subsequent publishing opened the tradition to anyone who wished to study it, effectively democratizing access. Today, Wicca is learned through books, websites, YouTube, and solitary practice — the initiatory coven structure is one option among many but no longer the only entry point.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Wicca has no authority to enforce apostasy rules. Leaving a coven involves leaving a community and may involve social consequences within that community (Wicca has its own politics and conflicts). Leaving Wicca entirely is simply a matter of ceasing to practice. Some Wiccan oaths of initiation include secrecy commitments; leaving the tradition while maintaining those secrets is the honorable approach. There is no spiritual punishment doctrine and no external authority to impose consequences.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Wiccaning (Saining)</strong> — a blessing ceremony for a newborn; the child is presented to the four elements and the Goddess and God; the child is welcomed into the universe and placed under divine protection; unlike baptism, the Wiccaning does not make the child a Wiccan — children are raised with exposure to Wicca but encouraged to choose their own path when they reach maturity</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage — Handfasting</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>The Wiccan wedding ceremony; the couple\'s hands are bound together (literally "tying the knot") with a cord; vows are exchanged; the binding may be "for a year and a day" (a renewable commitment) or "for this life" or "for all lifetimes" depending on the couple\'s preference</li>';
echo '<li>The ceremony is performed within the magic circle; the four elements are invoked; the God and Goddess bless the union</li>';
echo '<li>Handfasting has been adopted widely beyond Wicca as a popular alternative wedding ceremony</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Death — Crossing the Veil</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li>The dead are believed to cross to the Summerland — a peaceful, beautiful realm where the soul rests and reflects between incarnations; the Summerland is not permanent but a temporary resting place</li>';
echo '<li>The veil between the living and dead is thinnest at Samhain (October 31); ancestor communication and honoring the dead are central Samhain practices</li>';
echo '<li>Funerary customs vary by practitioner; some prefer burial (return to earth), others cremation (return to fire); the ceremony typically involves releasing the deceased with love and acknowledging their continuation in the Summerland</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Reincarnation</h3>';
echo '<p>Most Wiccans accept reincarnation — the soul rests in the Summerland between lives, then is reborn into a new body. The Wiccan concept is not precisely identical to the Hindu or Buddhist doctrine: there is no detailed karma system governing the quality of rebirth, and the process is understood as the soul\'s free choice rather than a mechanical consequence of actions. Gender in reincarnation: Wicca typically holds that the soul has no fixed gender and may incarnate in any gender across lives. Cross-species reincarnation is not a standard Wiccan teaching, though some practitioners accept it. The Threefold Law functions as the Wiccan karma equivalent within a single life, not necessarily across multiple lives.</p>';

// ECKANKAR
echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#553c9a;">⊕ Eckankar — Full Doctrinal Treatment</h2>';
echo '<p><strong>Theism:</strong> Monotheistic — SUGMAD (God) is the supreme being; the ECK (Holy Spirit as Sound and Light) is the divine current | <strong>Founded:</strong> 1965 CE, USA | <strong>Founder:</strong> Paul Twitchell (1908–1971) | <strong>Followers:</strong> ~50,000</p>';

echo '<h3>Faith and Belief</h3>';
echo '<p>Eckankar calls itself "The Ancient Science of Soul Travel." Its central claim is that the human being is Soul — a divine spark of God — and that Soul can consciously leave the physical body and travel through multiple inner spiritual planes (worlds of existence) toward reunion with SUGMAD (God). This is not metaphor but literal teaching: practitioners claim to experience out-of-body travel during sleep and meditation as real events with genuine spiritual content.</p>';
echo '<p>Eckankar\'s founder Paul Twitchell claimed to have been trained by a lineage of ECK Masters — spiritually advanced beings who have completed the human evolutionary journey and remain to guide seekers. The current Living ECK Master is Harold Klemp, who has led the organization since 1981 with the title "Mahanta, the Living ECK Master." The Mahanta is understood as the highest state of God-Consciousness on earth — the outer teacher whose inner presence guides initiates during their Soul Travel experiences.</p>';

echo '<h3>Doctrines</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>SUGMAD</strong> — the supreme, unknowable God; the source of all existence; too vast for direct human comprehension but approached through the ECK</li>';
echo '<li><strong>ECK (Audible Life Stream)</strong> — the Holy Spirit manifesting as Sound (the divine current heard in meditation) and Light (the divine current seen in the inner vision); the ECK flows from SUGMAD through all planes of existence and is the primary vehicle of spiritual experience</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Soul (Atma)</strong> — each individual is Soul — a conscious, eternal, divine spark; Soul\'s purpose is to gain experience and wisdom through incarnation in the lower worlds, progressing toward God-Realization</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Mahanta</strong> — the Living ECK Master; the outer teaching and guidance, and also the inner presence (the "Mahanta consciousness") that accompanies initiates on inner spiritual journeys; currently Harold Klemp</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The Spiritual Planes</strong> — existence is organized in multiple planes: Physical, Astral, Causal, Mental, Etheric, Soul (the first truly spiritual plane), and above that the God Worlds; Soul travels through these planes during spiritual exercises</li>';
echo '<li><strong>HU</strong> — the sacred name of God in Eckankar (pronounced "hue"); singing HU is the central spiritual practice; it is understood as a love song to God that opens the practitioner to the ECK current</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Doctrinal Controversies</h3>';
echo '<p>Eckankar has faced significant scholarly scrutiny. Critics have documented that Paul Twitchell plagiarized substantial portions of his early Eckankar books from the writings of Kirpal Singh (a Surat Shabd Yoga master) and Julian Johnson (author of <em>The Path of the Masters</em>), often changing only names and terms. Twitchell also fabricated his personal biography, claiming experiences and a lineage of masters that researchers have been unable to verify. The organization acknowledges some of these issues while defending Twitchell\'s spiritual authenticity. This history is relevant to the scholarly evaluation of Eckankar\'s doctrinal claims.</p>';

echo '<h3>Proselytism</h3>';
echo '<p>Eckankar engages in moderate outreach — publishing books and materials, maintaining a website, hosting introductory talks and seminars, and operating Eckankar centers in many cities. It does not engage in aggressive street proselytism. The tradition holds that Soul finds Eckankar when it is ready — the seeker must take the initiative, though Eckankar makes itself visible and accessible. Membership involves progression through a series of initiations that deepen the practitioner\'s connection to the ECK.</p>';

echo '<h3>Apostasy</h3>';
echo '<p>Members who leave Eckankar do so simply by ceasing their membership. There is no formal apostasy doctrine or punishment. However, Eckankar teachings hold that leaving the Living ECK Master\'s guidance has spiritual consequences — the practitioner loses the inner protection and guidance of the Mahanta and may slow their spiritual progress. This is a spiritual incentive to remain, not a coercive enforcement mechanism. Former members have organized communities online to process their experiences, and some accounts of the organization are critical of its culture and the pressure to maintain membership.</p>';

echo '<h3>Birth and Death</h3>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Birth</strong> — no formal birth ritual; children of Eckankar members are introduced to HU and the teachings from an early age; youth programs exist at Eckankar centers</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Death</strong> — death is understood as Soul leaving the physical body; it is not an ending but a transition to the next plane of existence; an experienced Eckist may consciously experience the moment of death as a continuation of their Soul Travel practice; no formal funeral liturgy is prescribed; memorial services typically involve singing HU and sharing memories</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Marriage</h3>';
echo '<p>Eckankar does not have a distinctive marriage ceremony. Members may be married in civil ceremonies or in Eckankar spiritual centers; the ceremony typically includes HU and readings from ECK scripture. Marriage is valued; celibacy is not emphasized as a spiritual path.</p>';

echo '<h3>Reincarnation and Karma</h3>';
echo '<p>Reincarnation is a central Eckankar doctrine. Soul incarnates repeatedly in the lower worlds (physical, astral, causal, mental planes) accumulating experience and working off karma until it achieves sufficient spiritual growth to ascend to the Soul Plane and beyond. Karma in Eckankar is understood as the law of cause and effect operating across multiple lives — unresolved karmic debts bring Soul back into incarnation to complete its learning. The Living ECK Master can "burn karma" for initiates — accelerating their spiritual progress by taking on some of their karmic burden. This is one of the most spiritually significant claims of Eckankar: that initiation into the tradition dramatically accelerates one\'s karmic resolution and therefore one\'s spiritual evolution.</p>';
echo '<p><strong>Gender in reincarnation</strong>: Eckankar accepts that Soul can incarnate in different genders across lives; gender is not essential to Soul\'s identity. <strong>Cross-species</strong>: Eckankar teaches that Soul progresses through mineral, plant, and animal forms before reaching human birth; this is not understood as downward transmigration (as in Hindu karma gone wrong) but as an evolutionary ascent through forms of increasing complexity.</p>';

